# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: call-of-duty-championship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] They currently operate three franchise teams, which compete in the *Valorant* Champions Tour (VCT), *Apex Legends* Global Series (ALGS) (branded as Crazy Thieves), the Call of Duty League (CDL) (branded as Los Angeles Thieves).
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] 100 Thieves was founded in 2017 by Matthew "Nadeshot" Haag, a former OpTic Gaming *Call of Duty* team captain, (MLG) X Games gold medalist, and 2014 Esports Athlete of the year.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In November 2017, 100 Thieves received a multimillion-dollar investment from Cleveland Cavaliers and Quicken Loans owner Dan Gilbert allowing the company to expand into a full-fledged esports organization.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On October 23, 2018, 100 Thieves announced that they finished their Series A funding round co-led by Scooter Braun and Drake, who both became co-owners when they raised $25 million.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Included in this round was Sequoia Capital, Ludlow Ventures, Courtside Ventures, WndrCo, Marc Benioff, Drew Houston, Green Bay Ventures, Tao Capital and Advancit Capital.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Their Series B funding round on July 16, 2019, was led by Artist Capital Management which raised $35 million.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Included in this round is Aglae Ventures, Groupe Arnault (controlling shareholder of Louis Vuitton Moet Hennessy).
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In March 2021, 100 Thieves signed a sponsorship deal with Truly Seltzer and Twisted Tea.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] They acquired gaming peripheral company Higround in October 2021, marking their first acquisition.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On December 2, 2021, 100 Thieves announced their Series C funding round, which raised $60 million.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In May 2022, 100 Thieves announced its intentions to publish a video game.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] It hired former Telltale Games CEO Pete Hawley as its Chief Product Officer to set up a studio.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In July, more than 10 members of 100 Thieves' content team were laid off.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Nadeshot launched his own energy drink, called Juvee, on October 4.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In January 2023, around 30 employees were laid off, including several lead staff members.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] That November, 100 Thieves announced it was laying off 20% of its workforce, affecting employees at its game studio and energy drink brand.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] These business units would also be spun off as separate companies in order to focus on esports and apparel.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On May 6, 2024, the Esports World Cup Foundation, funded by the Saudi Arabia Public Investment Fund and organizers of the Esports World Cup tournament series, announced the 30 organizations (known in the ESWC as Clubs) who would make up the Club Support Program, with 100 Thieves being one of them.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] This program gives teams a one-time six-figure stipend if an organization is willing to enter new esports as well as additional funding each year if they drive viewership and fan engagement to the Esports World Cup.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In December 2024, Nadeshot revealed that he would be taking a step back from 100 Thieves to pursue full-time content creation.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In September 2025, Nadeshot confirmed that he is no longer the CEO of 100 Thieves, but remains involved with the organization in other roles.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In February 2019, 100 Thieves announced their entrance in the Apex Legends competitive scene, signing Connor "Gigz" White, Justin "Teenage" Phipps, and Isiah "Lifted" Slowik as their first roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In August 2019, 100 Thieves announced Justin "JP2" Pate as their fourth roster member.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In the same month, 100 Thieves announced their exit from the Apex Legends scene, releasing their entire roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In October 2021, 100 Thieves returned to Apex Legends, signing the roster of Brendan "Onmuu" Pode, Alex "scuwry" Scala, and Nicholas "Vein" Hobbs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In February 2022, the team released Vein and signed Alan "Vaxlon" Gonzalez, with Tyler "Sickks" Clark joining later on as their new head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team placed 3rd in the 2022 Apex Legends Global Series World Championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In September 2023, 100 Thieves released their entire roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In November 2024, 100 Thieves announced the roster of Tyler "Dezignful" Gardner, Noyan "Genburten" Ozkose, and 100 Thieves content creator Timothy "iiTzTimmy" An, with Deston "Bronzey" Nguyen as the head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After being eliminated in the group stage of the 2024 Apex Legends Global Series World Championship, Dezignful announced that he would be exploring his options for next season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In March 2025, 100 Thieves announced the departures of Dezingful and iiTzTimmy and announced the signings of Josue "Phony" Ruiz and Evan "Verhulst" Verhulst to join Genburten for the 2025 season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In September 2025, Bronzey stepped down as head coach and was replaced by Balvarine.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In January 2026, 100 Thieves announced a collaboration with the Japanese esports organization Crazy Raccoon, branding the team as the "Crazy Thieves" for the Year 5 Championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The following month, Balvarine would step down as the team's head coach and was replaced by Daniel "Nihil" Freudenthal.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team started the season off signing the team of Kenneth "Kenny" Williams, Maurice "Fero" Henriquez, Sam "Octane" Larew, Austin "SlasheR" Liddicoat, and Ian "Enable" Wyatt.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] They placed 9th–12th at CWL Las Vegas 2019, qualifying for the Pro League Qualifiers and for the Pro League.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After this, they had to re-evaluate the roster, and acquired Preston "Priestahh" Greiner and head coach James "Crowder" Crowder on loans from FaZe Clan, with Fero getting benched.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At CWL Fort Worth 2019, the team finished 4th losing to Team Reciprocity, citing medical issues with player Priestahh and being replaced by Fero.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At CWL London 2019, the team won the organization's first trophy.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At CWL Anaheim 2019, the team won the organization's second trophy.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After the Pro League, 100 Thieves finished second in Division B, qualifying for Pro League playoffs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At the Pro League Playoffs, the team placed 5th–6th, losing to Gen.G esports.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In the 2019 Call of Duty World Championship, 100 Thieves finished second, with a loss to eUnited.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After initially announcing their intention to not join the Call of Duty League in 2019, 100 Thieves announced in November 2020 that they would enter the league as the "Los Angeles Thieves" after acquiring OpTic Gaming's slot.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In the 2022 season, the Los Angeles Thieves defeated the Atlanta FaZe to the win the 2022 Call of Duty League World Championship, bringing the organization their first ever world championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 10, 2025, 100 Thieves announced that their entry into the Counter-Strike 2 competitive scene, marking their return to *Counter-Strike* esports for the first time since October 2020.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The organization also announced the online casino Roobet as the team's title sponsor and the team will play under the name "100 Thieves Roobet".
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 12, the team made their first signings with the hirings of Graham "messioso" Pitt as Head of CS Operations and Sean "sgares" Gares as Head of FPS.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The latter had previously been head coach for their Valorant team and will be working with both the Counter-Strike 2 and Valorant divisions.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 13, 100 Thieves announced their first player in multi-time HLTV MVP Håvard "rain" Nygaard.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On December 19, 100 Thieves announced Lukas "gla1ve" Rossander as their head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On January 5, 2026, 100 Thieves announced the signings of André "Ag1l" Gil, Alex "poiii" Sundgren, and William "sirah" Kjærsgaard.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The following day, the team was finalized with the signing Nicolai "dev1ce" Reedtz.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In May 2025, 100 Thieves parted ways with Tensa as their head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In June 2025, Luis "iRemiix" Figueroa and Kamryn "Malenia" Mistry were hired as the team's new coaches with Malenia also being a substitute, while Billion would leave the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] A month later, Jacob "Nuk" Allen was signed to the roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 17, 100 Thieves announced that they would be leaving the Marvel Rivals competitive scene, releasing their entire roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On February 10, 2026, 100 Thieves announced that they have re-joined the Marvel Rivals scene as part of the Marvel Rivals Partner Program, re-signing Delenna, Malenia, TTK, Vinnie with IRemiix as the head coach to join the new additions of Bryce “Self” Pettit and Pol “Wyni” Carracedo.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On February 14, 2026, 100 Thieves announced their entry into the Rainbow Six Siege competitive scene as part of the R6 Partner Program.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On March 9, 100 Thieves announced their inaugural roster of Adam "Atom" Gutierrez, Arthur "GMZ" Oliveria, Roberto "Panbazou" Feliciano, Zachary "SpiriTz" Dionne, and Evan "Yoggah" Nelson with the coaching staff of Luiz "Kizi" Sirico and Kaique "Kpan" Pantojo.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On June 4, 2020, 100 Thieves Esports announced their entrance into the Valorant competitive scene through the signing of Spencer "Hiko" Martin.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Within three weeks of signing Hiko, the team was finalized.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team also signed Hector "FrosT" Rosario as their head coach but he was announced until months later.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The original team consisted of in-game leader Keane "Valliate" Alonso, Diondre "YaBoiDre" Bond, Zachary "Venerated" Roach, and Alfred "Pride" Choi.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] This team, however, did not last long; on August 14, 2020, the entire team, apart from Hiko, was released.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Shortly thereafter, the team went on to sign Counter-Strike: Global Offensive veterans Nick "nitr0" Cannella and in-game leader Joshua "steel" Nissan.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] 2 months later, the team was once again finalized after signing Peter "Asuna" Mazuryk and Quan "dicey" Tran from Immortals.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team went on to win the very first Valorant First Strike tournament, defeating TSM in the grand finals.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On January 26, 2021, the team brought in Jonathan "silenx" Huntington as a substitute in place of nitr0, due to nitr0's wife going into labor.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Nitr0 returned to the team shortly after.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On February 28, 2021, the team benched dicey in favor of another veteran CS:GO player, Ethan "Ethan" Arnold.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After the Masters 3 tourney, the team decided to call up their substitute Aaron "b0i" Thao to the starting roster, moved steel to the bench, and appointed nitr0 as full-time in-game leader.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team also added Johann "seven" Hernandez as a substitute.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Their 2021 season ended after falling to Cloud9 in the NA Last Chance Qualifier for Valorant Champions.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 23, dicey and b0i were dropped from the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Soon after, both steel and nitr0 departed the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] They started 2022 with the signing of in-game leader Adam "ec1s" Eccles and Hunter "BabyJ" Schline and promoting analyst Jovanni "Jovi" Vera to head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Shockingly, after two losses in the 2022 NA VCT Challengers Stage 1 group stage, ec1s and BabyJ were released; the team then acquired Sean "bang" Bezerra from TSM and Noah "jcStani" Smith from Kansas City Pioneers on loans and Ethan was appointed as in-game leader.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After being eliminated in the 2022 NA VCT Challengers group stage, the team parted ways with Jovi and hired Sean "sgares" Gares as head coach with Michael "Mikes" Hockom joining him as an assistant, and hiring Daniel "ddk" Kapadia as general manager.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On March 27, jcStani announced his free agency after his loan period ended with the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On April 12, Hiko announced his retirement from competitive Valorant but remained with the organization as a content creator.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] A couple days later, bang was fully bought out and the team then signed Derrek "Derrek" Ha, in-game leader Brenden "stellar" McGrath, and William "Will" Cheng, while Ethan was moved to the bench and later released.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team was able to qualify for 2022 Valorant Champions after beating The Guard in the grand finals of the NA Last Chance Qualifier.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team was then placed Group D alongside DRX, FURIA Esports, and Fnatic.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team finished the tournament 9-12th.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Following the end of the regular 2022 season, 100 Thieves released Will and signed XSET star player Matthew "Cryo" Panganiban, and Mikes was promoted to head coach, following Sgares's departure.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] 100 Thieves ended the year by winning the Red Bull Home Ground tournament #3 in Manchester with a 3–0 win over Cloud9 in December 2022.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In September 2022, 100 Thieves was selected as one of the thirty teams to be part of Riot Games' partnership program for the 2023 season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] During the season, they failed to qualify to Americas League playoffs and were also eliminated in their first match in the Americas Last Chance Qualifier.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On September 12, 2023, 100 Thieves announced the release of Derrek and stellar.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On September 25, 2023, 100 Thieves signed Tony "Zikz" Gray as head coach, who had previously been head coach for their League of Legends team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Mikes was moved back to assistant coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 1, 2023, 100 Thieves announced Daniel "eeiu" Vucenovic to the starting roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] 100 Thieves competed in the main event of Red Bull Home Ground #4 in Tokyo with Nicholas "NaturE" Garrison as a stand-in and interim in-game leader, and placed fifth.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On January 8, 2024, 100 Thieves rounded out their roster with in-game leader, Kelden "Boostio" Pupello.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Boostio, along with Zikz, previously won the 2023 Valorant Champions with Evil Geniuses.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The season started off poorly with 100 Thieves losing all their games in the Kickoff tournament and being eliminated.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In Americas Stage 1, they placed second in their group and qualified for the playoffs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] With a clean sweep of their playoff games including a 3–0 win over G2 Esports in the grand final, they became Stage 1 champions and qualified to Masters Shanghai as the first seed from Americas, earning a bye to the playoffs and 9 circuit points for the 2024 Valorant Champions.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At Shanghai, they placed 4th after beating FUT and Paper Rex but losing to both eventual finalists Gen.G and Team Heretics.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] With a 2–3 record in Americas Stage 2, the team made it into playoffs but placed 4th, ending their year one win away from qualifying to Champions.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On October 3, it was announced that Bang would be leaving after two and a half years with the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On October 8, Alexander "Zander" Dituri was announced as the new fifth member of the roster with Yury "frenya" Elkin and Rudi "rudi" Mcken joining the coaching staff later on.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After a subpar start to the year, being eliminated immediately from 2025 Kickoff, and not making it to Masters Toronto either, 100 Thieves placed second in the 2025 Esports World Cup qualifier and became one of four Americas teams to qualify for Riyadh.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] They lost both matches played at EWC and were eliminated in last place.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On July 19, Boostio was benched and Drew "Kess" Lee was added to the roster, while Zander would take over in-game leading duties.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In Stage 2, 100 Thieves finished with a 3–2 record in group stage, but were eliminated by Cloud9 in the Stage 2 playoffs and failed to qualify for Champions.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After being eliminated, 100 Thieves allowed all members of the roster and coaching staff to explore their options of the 2026 season as restricted free agents.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] During the offseason, majority of the roster and all of the coaching staff left, while Asuna and Cryo stayed.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 6, the team announced the signings of TSM trio Timothée "Timotino" Dupont, in-game leader Jordan "vora" Pulwer, and 2021 Valorant Champion Laurynas "Nbs" Kisielius as their new head coach with Erik "d00mbr0s" Sandgren as an assistant.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The following day, the team finalized their roster for the 2026 season by re-signing Bang, who departed the team the offseason prior.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 12, the team announced that Sgares would be returning to the team as the Head of FPS, primarily working with the Valorant and Counter-Strike 2 divisions.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On August 19, C4Lypso stepped down as head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On September 25, Harry "zelo" Davies was hired as the team's new head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On February 4, 2026, 100 Thieves released their entire roster (barring Lidyuh) and coaching staff, signing Misu, scaryshark32, terror, and zoriental with Tanishq "Tanizhq" Sabharwal as head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In April 2026, 100 Thieves released their entire roster and left the *Valorant Game Changer* scene.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On June 1, 2026, 100 Thieves announced a collaboration with Your Favorite Player (YFP) to form a new Valorant team to compete in the *Valorant Challengers* scene branded as "Your Favorite Thieves" or "YFT".
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] They inherited YFP's team that included David “atlas” Griffiths, Jaiden “devy” Mantz, Bradley “Muddy” Saephan, Ali “stallion” Kadhim, and Damion “XXiF” Cook.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In November 2020, 100 Thieves entered the Call of Duty: Warzone competitive scene announcing Thomas "Tommey" Trewren and Rhys "Rated Price" as their first players.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In October 2022, Tommey left the team, with Rated also leaving a month later.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In April 2025, 100 Thieves returned to the scene for the 2025 Esports World Cup, announcing the roster of Rasim "Blazt" Ogresevic, Gabe "GabeKunn" Kunn, Logan "Skullface" Greifelt, and Ethan "Ebatez" Bates as head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In October 2025, t100 Thieves exited the scene, releasing their entire roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In April 2018, 100 Thieves was announced as member of the Clash Royale League.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In the following months, 100 Thieves announced the roster of Eduadro "Eddie" Rojas-Torras, Jacob "Frost" Horsch, James "Pt105" Keresey, and Hoan "PureZuhn" Le, with Davis "Gilgamesh" Huang as head coach and William "Woody" Hix as the team's general manager.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In December 2018, 100 Thieves announced their departure from competitive Clash Royale.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In December 2017, 100 Thieves announced that they signed the former roster of Immortals which included players Bruno "BIT" Lima, Lincoln "fnx" Lau, Henrique "HEN1" Teles, Vito "kNgV-" Giuseppe, and Lucas "LUCAS1" Teles with Rodolfo "bLecker" Blecker as head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] However, the organization had issues with visas, resulting in the team being disbanded.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In late October 2019, 100 Thieves announced the signing of the former Renegades roster which included Aaron "AZR" Ward, Sean "Gratisfaction" Kaiwai, Joakim "jkaem" Myrbostad, Justin "jks" Savage, and Jay "Liazz" Tregillgas with Aleksandar "kassad" Trifunović as head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At IEM Beijing 2019, the team placed second in the tournament, losing to Astralis.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team placed 7th–8th at the ESL Season 10 Pro League Finals, losing to Fnatic.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In April 2020, head coach Kassad was mutually let go from the team and Chet "Chet" Singh was hired as the new head coach a month later.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On October 12, 2020, 100 Thieves announced their departure from the competitive CS:GO scene, citing complications with travel, a focus on European events, and COVID-19 as the main reasons behind the move.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In July 2018, 100 Thieves announced their entrance into the Fortnite: Battle Royale competitive scene, announcing the signings of Kenith, Archie "Parallax" Sharder, and Alex "Risker" Biamonte, with SirDimetrious joining a month later.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At the beginning of 2019, Risker and Parallax were released and the team signed Maurilio "Blind" Gramajo, Davis "Ceice" McClellan, Hayden "Elevate" Krueger, Brandon "Klass" Weaver, and Gabriel "Kyuzi" Harlos.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At the end of 2019, Blind, Kenith, and SirDimetrious were released, with the team signing Diego "Arkhram" Lima, Brendan "Falconer" Facloner, and Brett "grandmateets" Squires.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] At the Fortnite World Cup, Ceice and Elevate placed 3rd in the duos competition, while Arkhram and Falconer placed 5th.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In 2020, the team signed Martin "MrSavage" Andersen and Brodie "rehx" Franks, with Grandmateets, Klass, and Kyzui leaving the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In February 2021, Ceice and Elevate left the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The next year, 100 Thieves exited the Fortnite: Battle Royale competitive scene, releasing the remaining roster members.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] On November 20, 2017, 100 Thieves was accepted as a franchise organization for the 2018 NA LCS season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team signed Neil "pr0lly" Hammad as its head coach and Kim "Ssumday" Chan-ho, William "Meteos" Hartman, Ryu "Ryu" Sang-wook, Cody Sun, and Zaqueri "Aphromoo" Black for its starting roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team placed first in the spring split regular season with a 12–6 record, securing a bye into the semifinals.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Additionally, Aphromoo was voted as MVP of the spring split.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The first team they faced in the playoffs was Clutch Gaming, and 100 Thieves won 3–2, moving on to the finals, where they were swept 0–3 by Team Liquid in the finals.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] 100 Thieves' second-place finish qualified them for Rift Rivals 2018, an international tournament between the top three spring teams from Europe and North America.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team elected to use substitute player Đỗ "Levi" Duy Khánh in place of Meteos for the tournament.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Team Liquid, 100 Thieves, and Echo Fox competed against Europe's Fnatic, G2 Esports, and Splyce, going a combined 4–5 in the double round-robin group stage with 100 Thieves with a 1–2 record after a single win against Splyce.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In the best-of-five "relay race" finals, the team lost their game against Fnatic, contributing to North America's combined 1–3 loss to Europe.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Before the summer split, 100 Thieves traded Meteos to Flyquest, in exchange for their jungler, Andy "AnDa" Hoang.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Following this roster move, the team placed third in the regular season with a 10–8 record.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team won their first match 3–0 over FlyQuest, before losing 1–3 to Team Liquid in the semi-finals, then losing 2–3 in the third place match to Team SoloMid.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team's performance across both splits allowed them to qualify for the 2018 League of Legends World Championship in South Korea as North America's second seed.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team was drawn to Group D with Europe's Fnatic, China's Invictus Gaming, and Hong Kong's G-Rex.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Shortly after qualifying for the world championship, they replaced Cody Sun with substitute player Richard "Rikara" Oh.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] 100 Thieves finished third in their group with a 2–4 record, and 12th overall, not qualifying for the knockout stage.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In 2019, the team extended top laner Ssumday's contract, while Ryu moved to an assistant position.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Cody Sun and Rikara opted to leave the team, and they were replaced by Choi "huhi" Jae-hyun and Bae "Bang" Jan-sik.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Partway through the spring split, Huhi was benched in favor for Max "Soligo" Soong, but despite attempts at change, the team finished the spring split in dead last, with a 4–14 record, and elected to make additional roster changes for summer.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Huhi left the team, and Maurice "Amazing" Stückenschneider joined to replace AnDa, who was moved to the academy roster along with Ryu.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] A month into the split, the team replaced Soligo with Ryu from the academy roster, and also swapped Ssumday with Aaron "FakeGod" Lee, as LCS rules required at least 3 North American residents on the starting roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team finished the summer split in eighth place and did not qualify for the post–season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] 100 Thieves began the 2020 season with the announcement that Chris "PapaSmithy" Smith would be joining the team as the new general manager.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Tony "Zikz" Gray was the next addition to the roster, replacing pr0lly as head coach, and both Meteos and Cody Sun rejoined the team for the second time, alongside new additions William "Stunt" Chen and Tommy "Ryoma" Le.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Ryu, Amazing, Bang and Aphromoo all left the team, with FakeGod rejoining Academy and Ssumday rejoining the main roster.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In spring, the team finished third in the regular season with a 10–8 record, and qualified for post–season for the first time since 2018.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] However once in the playoffs, they were swept 0–3 by Cloud9, and then lost 2–3 to Team SoloMid in the losers' bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After an 1–5 start in the summer split, the team parted ways with players Meteos and Stunt, and called up academy players Juan "Contractz" Garcia and Philippe "Poome" Lavoie-Giguere to replace them.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team finished in seventh at the end of the summer split with a 7–11 record, and were seeded into the loser's bracket of the playoffs, where they would be swept 0–3 by Evil Geniuses to finish their 2020 season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The 2021 season started with the team signing Can "Closer" Çelik, Victor "FBI" Huang, Tanner "Damonte" Damonte, and a returning Huhi from Golden Guardians.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Ry0ma (renamed from Ryoma) and Poome were moved to the academy roster, while Cody Sun and Contractz both left the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team also added Aleš "Freeze" Kněžínek and Ham "Lustboy" Jang-sik to the coaching staff.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The season started off with the preseason Lock−In tournament, and the team starting strong, placing first in their group, before sweeping Immortals 2–0 in the first round of the knock−out stage.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In the semifinals they faced Cloud9, and despite winning the first two games, were reverse swept to lose 2–3 in the series, and finish 3rd/4th in the tournament.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In week 5 of the spring split, the team decided to bring back Ry0ma as their starter and sent Damonte to academy.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] They finished the spring split in third place, and in the Mid-Season Showdown, were swept 0–3 by Cloud9, before picking up a 3–0 win of their own against Dignitas in the losers bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team faced Team SoloMid next, and fell 1–3, and were eliminated from playoffs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After a fourth-place finish in the spring split, the team parted ways with head coach Zikz and hired Bok "Reapered" Han-gyu as his replacement.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Prior to the start of the summer split, 100 Thieves signed Felix "Abbedagge" Braun from the LEC, and Ry0ma was subsequently sent back to academy, while Damonte was dropped by the organization.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The revamped roster would go on to finish second in the regular season, with a record of 29–16.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team won their first playoff match 3–2 against Evil Geniuses, before falling 2–3 to Team Liquid.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In the losers' bracket, 100 Thieves defeated Cloud9 3–1 to set up a finals rematch against Team Liquid.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] This time around, 100 Thieves defeated Team Liquid in a 3–0 sweep, to win the 2021 LCS Championship and qualify for the 2021 League of Legends World Championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team's performance secured them a bye into Group B alongside China's Edward Gaming, Korea's T1, and Japan's DetonatioN FocusMe.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team finished third in their group, with a 3–3 record, and were eliminated from the tournament, placing 9th–12th overall and ending their season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In 2022, the team announced all five players would be returning, with academy top laner Milan "Tenacity" Oleksij as a sixth man.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Alfonso "Mithy" Rodriguez also joined the coaching staff in the off−season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Once again, 100 Thieves were atop their group in the Lock−In tournament, however they were upset 0–2 by Dignitas in the quarterfinals of the Knock−Out stage, and eliminated early.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Through the first round robin of the spring split, 100 Thieves accumulated a 5–4 record, putting them in a three-way tie for third place.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] 100 Thieves ultimately ended the spring split with a record of 12–6, securing themselves third place.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In the first round of Playoffs, they swept Cloud 9 3–0 to advance to the winner bracket finals, where they came back from a 0–2 deficit to reverse sweep Team Liquid and advance to Grand Finals.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] There, they lost 0–3 to Evil Geniuses, denying 100 Thieves back to back championships.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Following a group stage exit at the 2022 World Championship, General manager PapaSmithy and coaches Repeared, Mithy, and Freeze parted ways with the team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] For the 2023 season, 100 Thieves released the entire roster except Closer, signing veterans Yiliang "Doublelift" Peng and Søren "Bjergsen" Bjerg and promoting Alan "Busio" Cwalina from the academy, and Tenacity to full-time top laner.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team also hired Christopher "Kaas" Oudheusden as their new head coach with Erlend "Nukeduck" Holm joining as an assistant and promoting Joseph "JungleJuice" Jang as general manager.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After a 5–8 start to the Spring Split, Kaas and 100 Thieves parted ways and Nukeduck was promoted to interim head coach with Danny "Dan Dan" Comte joining as an assistant from the challengers team.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Following a quick exit in Spring playoffs, Bjergsen announced his retirement.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After Bjergsen's retirement, the team announced their new head coach in Jang "Cain" Nu-ri and the signing of Lim "Quid" Hyeon-seung as their new mid laner.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team also brought back Ssumday as Tenacity decided to move to content creation.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team finished with a 7–11 record and placed 7th-8th in the summer split championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] For the 2024 season, the team parted ways with the whole roster and coaching staff except for Quid, signing Rayan "Sniper" Shoura, Kim "River" Dong-woo, Brandon "Meech" Choi, and Bill "Eyla" Nguyen.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team also announced Greyson "Goldenglue" Gilmer as their new head coach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team finished 5th-8th in the Spring playoffs with a 10–4 record in the regular season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] During the Summer split, Meech was benched and the team signed Frank "Tomo" Lam.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The team finished the regular season with a 3–4 record and finished 3rd in the Summer playoffs and qualified for the 2024 World Championship play-in, where they would be eliminated by PSG Talon.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In November 2024, Tomo was released and FBI was re-signed as the new starting bot laner.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] They finished the regular season of Split 1 in first place, but finished as runner-ups in the playoffs, losing to Team Liquid 0–3 in the grand finals In Split 2, they finished 3rd in the regular season standings and placed top 6 in the playoffs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In July 2025, 100 Thieves announced that they would be exiting the LTA and League of Legends competitive scene after the 2025 season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In August 2025, Nishp "Dhokla" Doshi was added to the roster as a sixth man.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In October 2025, T1 defeated 100 Thieves at the 2025 Worlds tournament, resulting in their withdrawal from *League of Legends*.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In May 2025, 100 Thieves announced their entry into the Street Fighter competitive scene with signing of Sean "Shine" Simpson.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] After placing 25th-36th in the 2025 Esports World Cup, Shine was quietly released and 100 Thieves exited the Street Fighter competitive scene.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In May 2025, 100 Thieves announced their entry into the Teamfight Tactics competitive scene with the roster of Joseph "Dishsoap" Goldsmith, Yoo "Kiyoon" Ki-yoon, Rereplay, and Spencer "Spencer" Zhou.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] In December 2025, the roster was released and 100 Thieves exited the scene.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The 100 Thieves Compound is a 15,000 square foot esports, entertainment, and apparel hub, located in Culver City, California.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] It has four sports training rooms: the Rocket Mortgage League of Legends training room, the AT&T Valorant training room, the Totino's Fortnite training room, and the League of Legends Academy training room.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] It also has a content studio, which is worth around half a million dollars.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Other areas include the Cash App Lounge, the Totino's basketball court, many business operation areas and four streaming pods.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] Chairs, catering, and PCs are provided by Secretlab, Chipotle and NZXT respectively.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] It was formerly known as the 100 Thieves Cash App Compound.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/100-thieves] The compound served as an LA County vote center for the 2020 United States presidential election.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] The **2017 CWL Global Pro League** was a *Call of Duty: Infinite Warfare* tournament on PlayStation 4 that occurred on April 21-July 30, 2017.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] The 2017 CWL Global Pro League consisted of 2 Stages, with 16 teams from North America, Europe and the APAC region participating.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] The 16 teams were split into 4 different pools with the top 2 teams from each pool advancing to playoffs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] The top 3 teams from each pool advanced to Stage 2, while the fourth place team had to go to the relegation playoffs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] A total of $700,000 prize money was given out during Stage 1.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] All 16 teams received $12,500 for participating while the 8 teams which qualified for playoffs played for another $500,000.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] The 4 bottom teams from Stage 1 participated in the relegation tournament against 4 other teams in a double-elimination bracket for the final 4 spots in Stage 2.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] A total of $700,000 prize money was given out during Stage 2.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] The top 3 teams from all Stage 1 groups and the 4 teams which qualified via the relegation tournament participated in Stage 2.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2017-cwl-global-pro-league] All 16 teams also qualified for the 2017 Call of Duty Championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] The **2018 CWL Pro League** was a *Call of Duty: WWII* tournament on PlayStation 4 that occurred on January 23-July 29, 2018.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] The 2018 CWL Global Pro League consisted of 2 Stages, with 16 teams from North America, Europe and the APAC region participating.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] The 16 teams were split into 2 different Divisions with the top 4 teams from each Division advancing to playoffs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] The top 6 teams from each pool advanced to Stage 2, while the bottom 2 teams from each Division have to go to the relegation playoffs.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] A total of $700,000 prize money will be given out during Stage 1.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] All 16 teams will receive $12,500 for participating while the 8 teams which qualified for playoffs will play for another $500,000.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] Week 1 of Division A took place from January 23, 2018, until February 1, 2018, with week 2 taking place from February 20, 2018, until March 1, 2018.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] Week 1 of Division B took place from February 6, 2018, until February 15, 2018, with week 2 taking place from March 14, 2018, until March 22, 2018.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] Teams which placed among the bottom 2 teams in their Division during Stage 1 have until 6pm ET on April 13, 2018, to submit a roster and were allowed to replace 2 players.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] The top 4 teams qualified for Stage 2 of the 2018 CWL Pro League.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] AA total of $700,000 prize money will be given out during Stage 2.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] The top 6 teams from all Stage 1 groups and the 4 teams which qualified via the relegation tournament participated in Stage 2.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] All 16 teams also qualified for the 2018 Call of Duty Championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] Teams which placed among the top 6 teams in their Division during Stage 1 have until 6pm ET on May 7, 2018, to submit a roster and were allowed to replace 2 players.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2018-cwl-pro-league] Luminosity Gaming holds the tiebreak against compLexity Gaming based on over map win percentage.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The **2019 CWL Pro League** was the *Call of Duty: Black Ops 4* league on PlayStation 4 which took place from February through July, 2019.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The 2019 CWL Global Pro League will consist of a single stage, with 16 teams from North America, Europe and the APAC region participating.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The 16 teams will be split into 2 different divisions.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] Unlike previous years, teams will also play against teams from the other division.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] Teams will be able to make changes to their roster throughout the season, with matches being broadcast on Monday through Thursday.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The top teams will qualify for the CWL Finals.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] In the event of two or more teams having the same win–loss record at the conclusion of the Regular Season, final placing will be determined via tiebreaker rules.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] If these tiebreakers cannot break a tie, the tied teams will be scheduled to play a best-of-five round-robin tiebreaker.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] A coin-flip will determine which team will act as home and away for pick ban process.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] After each team has played all other tied Teams in the tiebreaker, their records of games won and games lost will be used to break the tie.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] If there is a tie involving more than two teams and a tiebreaker resolved the tie for a team(s), but leaves at least two teams tied, the tie(s) that remains will be broken by starting over with the Head to Head Match winning percentage tiebreaker.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] 16 teams from around the world will participate in the CWL Pro League.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The top four teams from CWL Las Vegas will automatically qualify for the CWL Pro League while teams placing 5th - 32nd will fight for the remaining 12 CWL Pro League spots, at a qualification event that will take place in January at the MLG Arena in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] A total of 16 teams, spread across 2 Divisions, participate during the Regular Season of the Pro League.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] Each team will play 22 matches: two Best of Five series against the other teams in their Division and one Best of Five series against the eight teams in the other Division.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The top 4 teams from each Division will directly qualify for the Playoff Bracket while the bottom 4 teams will have to play in the Play-In Bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] Matches will be played from February 4 through July 5.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] FaZe Clan acquired the Red Reserve roster and the team's spot on 20 April 2019.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] Denial Esports acquired the Overtime eSports roster and the organization's spot on 29 January 2019.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] On 31 May 2019, Denial Esports closed its doors and the team continued under the UNITS name.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] Elevate acquired the Excelerate Gaming roster and the organization's spot on 19 April 2019.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The playoffs will take place from July 19–21, 2019 at the Miami Beach Convention Center.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The play-in bracket is a single-elimination bracket consisting of the teams who placed 5th–8th in their division during regular-season play.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] Once two teams remain in the play-in bracket, those teams will be moved to round one of the playoff bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The playoff bracket is a ten-team double-elimination bracket which consists of the two teams who qualified via the play-in bracket and the top four teams from each division of regular-season play.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The 4th-placed team from each division will be placed in the first round of the winners' bracket, facing one of the two teams which qualified via the play-in bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2019-cwl-pro-league] The Final 3 consists of the Winners Bracket Round 4 winners who enter in the Final, the Winners Bracket Round 4 losers and the winners of the Losers Bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] The **2020 Call of Duty League season** was the inaugural season for the Call of Duty League, an esports league based on the video game franchise Call of Duty.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] The Call of Duty League began a partnership with YouTube to become the exclusive streaming service for the league.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] At least 331,000 viewers watched the grand final of the CDL championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] On July 4, Philip “Momo” Whitfield was fired from the league after several allegations of sexual misconduct surfaced on the internet.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Ten days later, Ben “Benson” Bowe revealed he's no longer working with the league.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Although his legal counsel "advised him not to say why", some reported it was due to similar reasons to Momo.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Thomas "Chance" Ashworth worked with Miles Ross for the rest of the season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] On July 10, the league added Landon “LandO” Sanders and Jeremy “StuDyy” Astacio to become the third casting pair in the wake of Momo and Benson departing.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Atlanta FaZe, Florida Mutineers, OpTic Gaming Los Angeles, Minnesota ROKKR.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Dallas Empire, Los Angeles Guerrillas, New York Subliners, Seattle Surge.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Chicago Huntsmen, London Royal Ravens, Paris Legion, Toronto Ultra.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Atlanta FaZe, London Royal Ravens, New York Subliners, OpTic Gaming Los Angeles.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Florida Mutineers, Minnesota ROKKR, Paris Legion, Toronto Ultra.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Chicago Huntsmen, Dallas Empire, Los Angeles Guerrillas, Seattle Surge.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: London Royal Ravens, New York Subliners, OpTic Gaming Los Angeles, Paris Legion.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Chicago Huntsmen, Los Angeles Guerrillas, Minnesota ROKKR, Seattle Surge.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Dallas Empire, Florida Mutineers, OpTic Gaming Los Angeles, Seattle Surge.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: Atlanta Faze, Chicago Huntsmen, Minnesota ROKKR, Toronto Ultra.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams not in attendance: New York Subliners, London Royal Ravens, Paris Legion, Los Angeles Guerrillas.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] The playoffs and 2020 Call of Duty League Championship began on August 19 and concluded on August 30, 2020.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] All twelve teams competed in the playoffs, and all matches were played online.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Best-of-9 with the team from the Winner's Bracket (WB) starting the match up 1–0.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2020-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams in the 2020 season competed for a prize pool of US$4.6 million in the playoffs, with the payout detailed below.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The **2021 Call of Duty League season** was the second season for the Call of Duty League, an esports league based on the video game franchise Call of Duty.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] For the 2021 season, the twelve teams are evenly split into two groups of six teams each.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The season consists of five stages, with teams playing group play matches over the course of three weeks to determine seeding for that stage's Major.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] For Stage 1, the finalists of 2020 season Dallas Empire and Atlanta FaZe got to pick which teams plays in which group, with Dallas Empire first getting to pick a team for the group of Atlanta FaZe, followed by Atlanta FaZe picking a team for the group of Dallas Empire.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The team which was picked by Dallas Empire for the group of Atlanta FaZe then got to pick a team for the group of Dallas Empire, with this process continuing until both groups consist of 6 teams.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The six teams in each group will then play each other over the course of three weeks to determine seeding, with teams being awarded 10 CDL Points for each victory.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] For Stage 2, the top two teams from the Stage 1 Major will have the first two picks for the Stage 2 groups, repeating the same process before Stage 1 kicked off.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The prize pool distribution has changed heavily since the 2020 season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] This is due to the increase of the prize pool as well as all 12 teams qualifying for each major tournament.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] There is $500,000 for each major event and $2,500,000 for the playoffs making a total of about $5,000,000 for the whole season in prizes.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 1 group stages began on February 11, 2021, and ended on February 28.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 1 Major ran from March 3 to March 7, 2021.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Atlanta FaZe won the Major, with the Dallas Empire as the runners-up.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 2 group stages began on March 18, 2021, and ended on April 4.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Starting with Stage 2, Crossroads Hardpoint and Garrison Search & Destroy were removed from the list of maps being played, with Apocalypse Hardpoint and Express Search & Destroy being added.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 2 Major ran from April 7 to April 11, 2021.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Toronto Ultra won the Major, with the Atlanta FaZe as the runners-up.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 3 group stages began on April 22, 2021, and ended on May 9.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Matches were played on Thursday through Sunday.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 3 Major ran from May 13 until May 16, 2021.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Atlanta FaZe won their second Major of the season, with the New York Subliners as the runners-up.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 4 group stages began on May 27, 2021, and ended on June 13.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Starting with Stage 4, Checkmate Search & Destroy was removed from the list of maps being played, with Standoff Search & Destroy being added.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 4 Major ran from June 17 to June 20, 2021.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] For the first time since March 2020 the league moved back to playing on LAN.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Atlanta FaZe won their third Major of the season, with the Dallas Empire as the runners-up.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 5 group stages began on July 8, 2021, and will end on July 25.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Matches are played on Thursday through Sunday.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 5 Major ran from July 29 to August 1, 2021.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] Minnesota ROKKR won their first Major of the season after being down 0–4 in the finals with the Toronto Ultra as the runners-up.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The 2021 Call of Duty League Championship began on August 19 and concluded on August 22, 2021.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2021-call-of-duty-league-season] The top eight teams competed in the Championship, and all matches were played in Los Angeles.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The **2022 Call of Duty League season** was the third season for the Call of Duty League, an esports league based on the video game franchise Call of Duty.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Before the start of the 2022 season, Envy Gaming announced that it would be merging with OpTic Gaming, resulting in the Dallas Empire being renamed to OpTic Texas.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] As a result of the merger, the Chicago franchise spot became vacant, with the vacant spot being taken by a new franchise based in Boston, named the Boston Breach.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] On January 21, the League announced that Esports Engine will become their official broadcasting partner for the 2022 season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Shoutcasters Clint "Maven" Evans and Joe "Merk" DeLuca returned, although they were not given offers to return until just before the beginning of the season.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] In an interview with *Dot Esports*, general manager Daniel Tsay claimed that contract negotiations prevented from addressing their absence and stated that the pair will only call the Majors, playoffs, and Champs weekend.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Lottie Van-Praag and Jess Brohard both departed and were replaced by Loviel "Velly" Cardwell and Guy "Blaze" Spencer as desk host stage host, respectively.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Alyssa "Allycxt" Parker was added as desk analyst, alongside a returning Anthony "NAMELESS" Wheeler.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The Kickoff classis ran from January 21 to January 23, 2022.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The tournament was won by Toronto Ultra, with Seattle Surge coming in second.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The 2022 Kickoff Classic saw less viewership compared to its previous seasons, peaking at just under 80,000 concurrent viewers, compared to a 107,000 peak viewership from 2021.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] For the 2022 season, teams will play at four Majors on a hybrid online/LAN model.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Each Major will take place over the course of 4 weeks, with each team playing online qualifying matches during the first three weeks against five random teams.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] After these three weeks the standings will be used to seed the teams for the major, with the bottom 4 teams starting in the Elimination Bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] In the middle of the season professional and amateur players will play against each other in a Pro-am tournament, and a Call of Duty: Warzone tournament featuring Call of Duty League pro players, streamers, and other influencers will be organized as well.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] To start the season, all twelve teams played against each other on January 21 through January 23, 2022, at the Esports Stadium Arlington in Arlington, Texas.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Two weeks later, on February 4 through February 6, the 2022 season officially started with the first matches being played online.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The online qualifiers for Major I ended on February 20, with the Major being hosted by OpTic Texas on March 3 through March 6.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Major II online qualifiers took place from March 11 through March 27, with the Major taking place from March 31 through April 3, hosted by Minnesota ROKKR.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Before the start of Major III, the midseason events will place with an online all-star weekend on April 9 and April 10.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Two weeks later on April 24, the CDL Warzone Pacific tournament took place which saw four players from all twelve teams fighting until the last man standing.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] From May 5 through May 8, the Pro-Am Classic took place, which saw the twelve CDL teams being joined by the four best Challengers teams in a tournament with the winning team taking home $100,000.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] After the midseason events concluded, Major III was hosted by Toronto Ultra from June 2 through June 5, with the online qualifiers taking place from May 13 through May 29.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The final Major of the season was hosted by New York Subliners, with the online qualifiers taking place from July 1 through July 17 and the Major itself taking place on July 21 through July 24.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The season concluded with the 2022 Call of Duty Championship, from August 4 through August 7, at the Galen Center in Los Angeles, California.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 1 group stage began on February 4, 2022, and ended on February 20.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 1 Major ran from March 3 through March 6, 2022.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The Major was won by *OpTic Texas* after defeating *Atlanta FaZe* 5–2 in the finals.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 2 group stage began on March 11, 2022, and ended on March 27.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 2 Major took place from March 31 through April 3, 2022, and was won by *Los Angeles Guerrillas* with *Atlanta FaZe* once again coming in second.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] From May 5 through May 8, 2022, all twelve Call of Duty League teams alongside four Challengers teams competed against each other.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The teams were put into 4 groups of 4, with three CDL teams and one Challengers team in each group.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Teams played the other three teams in their group once, with the top 2 from each group advancing to a single elimination bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The tournament was won by the New York Subliners, with the Los Angeles Thieves coming in second.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 3 group stage began on May 13, 2022, and ended on May 29.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] As part of Stage 3, the Call of Duty League introduced Bounty Week.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] From May 20 through May 22 all twelve teams played single series with $10,000 on the line for during series.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 3 Major took place from June 2 through June 5, 2022.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The major was won by Seattle Surge, with Atlanta FaZe coming in second.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] Stage 4 group stage began on June 24, 2022, and ended on July 10.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The Stage 4 Major took place from July 14 through July 17, 2022.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] It was won by Los Angeles Thieves, with New York Subliners coming in second.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The 2022 Call of Duty League Championship took place from August 4 through August 7, 2022.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/2022-call-of-duty-league-season] The top eight teams from the regular seasons standings competed in a Double Elimination bracket.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] The **Call of Duty Championship** is an annual *Call of Duty* tournament held at the end of each competitive season to determine the year's World Champion.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] To determine qualification, teams must qualify through events before the World Championship.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] Players must be at least 18 years of age as of the beginning of the tournament in order to participate.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] The inaugural tournament was first held in 2013 on *Call of Duty: Black Ops II* for the Xbox 360 and was won by Fariko Impact.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] In 2014, playing *Call of Duty: Ghosts*, Complexity Gaming won the $400,000 championship prize.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] The 2015 iteration of the event was won by Denial eSports with team consisting of Chris "Replays" Crowder, Dillon "Attach" Price, James "Clayster" Eubanks, and Jordan "JKap" Kaplan.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] The 2016 iteration occurred 2–4 September 2016, unlike previous ones held in the spring, with a two million dollar prize pool.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] It was announced on June 8, 2016, that the championship will take place along with Call of Duty XP which will reveal the Infinite Warfare Multiplayer Trailer.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] Team EnvyUs won the event, with a line-up of JKap, SlasheR, Apathy, and John (who was named MVP of the event).
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] In 2020, Activision and Sony Mobile announced the inaugural *Call of Duty: Mobile* Championship would begin on April 30.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] However, in December, Activision canceled the Mobile Grand Finals due to the COVID-19 pandemic, and distributed the $750,000 prize pool between the seven teams who qualified for the Finals.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] The 2021 Call of Duty League season began January 23, 2021.
[src:call-of-duty-championship/call-of-duty-championship] In April 2021, Activision announced the 2021 *Call of Duty: Mobile* Championship would begin on June 3.
